clib4's pthread_kill only sets a raw Exec signal bit -- the SIGUSR1 handler
never runs, so signal-based suspension could not stop a thread executing
bytecode (a pure-compute thread hung GC forever; verified by a MT allocation
stress with a spinner thread).  Replace delivery with cooperative polling:

- thread.c: amiga suspendLoop parks by polling thread->suspend (usleep loop;
  sigsetjmp still spills registers for GC root scanning); threadPollSuspend()
  exported; suspend_pending_count gates the poll, bumped in
  suspendThread/suspendAllThreads, dropped in resume*.
- interp-indirect.h (switch interpreter): poll the gate each dispatch; only
  when a suspension is pending is threadSelf() consulted.

Verified: 4 allocator threads + a 1.3e9-iteration compute spinner + System.gc()
complete correctly (sums equal, spinner stops, exit 0); 37/37 conformance and
the zero-flag -cp launch unaffected.  Note: only the (default) switch
interpreter variant polls; THREADED/DIRECT builds would need the same hook.

