From e38273c93d95600366610a2afd88f8ebd1773d23 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Richard Gibbs <wofderfs@googlemail.com>
Date: Wed, 10 Jun 2026 22:28:11 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 09/10] Fix clib4 exit wedge: self-terminate all Java threads
 on VM exit

clib4 exit() waits for every pthread child process to terminate before
tearing down the shared context; a Java thread still alive when the
exiting thread calls exit() suspends the process forever ("Parent
suspended, waiting for child to exit").  Headless runs were fine (the
finalizer/reference-handler condvar notify from terminateVMThreads
sufficed), but an AWT/Swing run leaves the EDT, AWT-Shutdown, the Amiga
event pump and the Java2D Disposer alive at System.exit().

Fix (cooperative, no async thread kill exists on clib4):
- exitWakeAllThreads() (thread.c): interrupt every attached thread out
  of Object.wait/sleep, and open the interpreter's dispatch-poll gate --
  THREAD_POLL_SUSPEND is gated on suspend_pending_count, so vm_exiting
  alone was never observed by running threads (the key bug).
- threadPollSuspend(): with vm_exiting set, any thread except the
  exiting one self-terminates (exitDetachAndDie: unlink from the thread
  list, drop threads_count, pthread_exit).
- amiga_exit() (init.c): wake-all, then drain getThreadsCount() to 1
  (re-interrupting periodically -- a woken thread can re-enter wait
  before its next poll), bounded at 3s, with a remaining-thread name
  dump diagnostic before exit().

Verified on qemu-java: SwingTest (full AWT thread complement) exits with
no Cleanup_hook wedge and no zombie CLI; headless -cp HelloWorld
regression unaffected.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/init.c   | 25 +++++++++++++++++++++-
 src/thread.c | 60 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
